  "method": "We propose a unified masked-prediction framework for non-text, non-image data called Structure- and Alignment-aware Masked Modeling (SAMM). SAMM treats graphs, time series, and heterogeneous sensor streams as token sequences enriched with structure. Tokenization is modality-specific but follows a common interface: each token carries a value embedding, a position/structure embedding, and a type embedding. For time series and sensor streams, we form variable-length temporal patches via change-point detection or fixed windows (with overlap) and optionally add frequency-domain tokens from short-time Fourier or wavelet transforms. For graphs, both nodes and edges become tokens, and attention is biased by graph distances and edge types; we also allow subgraph tokens produced by a lightweight pooling operator. Tokens from all sources are projected with shallow, modality-specific linear layers into a single fusion transformer, avoiding heavy encoders while preserving modality identity via type and structure embeddings.\n\nMasking is a mixture of random, structure-aware, and importance-aware policies. In streams, we mask contiguous spans, full channels, and frequency bands; in graphs, we mask nodes, edges, and coherent subgraphs (communities or k-hop balls). To make masking informative rather than arbitrary, we maintain a fast rationale scorer that estimates per-token importance from current representations; we sample a fixed budget of hard masks from high-importance tokens and fill the remainder with random or structure-contiguous masks to cover both critical and background context. We also apply modality dropout at sequence level (e.g., blank all tactile tokens while keeping vision) to force cross-sensor prediction.\n\nPrediction targets are chosen to avoid regression-to-the-mean and to match measurement noise. For continuous values, we predict discrete latent codes produced by a small vector-quantizer trained jointly with dequantization noise, plus an auxiliary residual head for fine error correction. Stream decoders predict both time-domain tokens and spectro-temporal tokens to capture local dynamics and periodicity; graph decoders predict masked node/edge attributes and edge existence. We optimize a multitask objective: masked-token cross-entropy on codes and L1/L2 on residuals; a cross-sensor contrastive alignment that brings co-temporal segments from different modalities together and pushes negatives apart; a pairwise matching loss that discriminates correctly synchronized pairs from time-shifted or modality-mismatched pairs; and a temporal-ordering loss on shuffled spans. For paired modalities with expected near-monotonic timing (e.g., audio–text, audio–vibration), we compute a soft alignment path from cross-modal similarities and add a regularizer that increases path sharpness and monotonicity while allowing small warps.\n\nArchitecturally, SAMM uses a single fusion transformer with relative position encodings for time and attention biases for graph topology. Lightweight per-modality heads share the backbone and are linked by cross-attention during decoding so that predictions for one stream can directly condition on hidden states from another when it is unmasked. Training follows a curriculum: begin with shorter spans, lower mask ratios, and mostly random masks; ramp up to higher ratios with larger contiguous blocks, more structure-aware subgraph masks, and more frequent modality dropouts. A compute-aware data scheduler mixes datasets and sensor pools based on learned utility and repetition half-lives, allocating training steps where they yield the greatest marginal improvement. At finetuning time, we freeze most of the backbone and attach small task heads (forecasting, anomaly detection, link prediction, node classification, imputation), optionally continuing masked objectives at low weight for stability.\n\nIn deployment, SAMM enables: imputation under missing sensors by reconstructing masked modalities; transfer across domains via shared discrete codebooks and alignment; and robust downstream performance with few labels due to structure- and importance-aware pretraining. Ablations vary tokenization granularity, mask composition, discretization vs pure regression, alignment regularization, and compute-aware scheduling to characterize what matters most per domain.",
  "rationale": "Masked prediction works when tokens, masks, and targets reflect the data’s structure and uncertainty. For streams, contiguity, channel correlations, and time–frequency duality matter; for graphs, masking should respect topology and community structure. Importance-aware masking focuses learning capacity on informative regions while retaining coverage of background context, echoing how masked language modeling benefits from content words but still sees function words. Discrete reconstruction targets stabilize training for continuous signals and avoid blurry averages; residual heads keep precision. Cross-modal contrastive and matching losses encourage the model to use complementary sensors rather than treating them as noise, and a soft alignment-path regularizer makes masked prediction feasible under time warps without requiring exact frame alignment.\n\nThe compute-aware data scheduler acknowledges that heterogeneous data pools contribute unequally and saturate with repetition, so it allocates pretraining steps and mask types where they are most valuable. Together, these choices adapt the masked-prediction principle beyond text and images by aligning the masking unit to structure (spans, subgraphs, channels), the prediction target to noise and ambiguity (discrete codes plus residuals), and the objective to cross-sensor alignment and discrimination.",
