  "method": "We propose MASK-FLEX, a unified masked-prediction pretraining recipe for graphs, time series, and multi-sensor streams. The core idea is to reconstruct strategically masked structure and signals from their context with a modality-aware encoder/decoder and a set of objectives tailored to data type and deployment constraints. MASK-FLEX uses multi-scale, structure-aware masks; a graph encoder with a global context token; a continuous-time stream encoder for irregular sensor data; and a lightweight reconstruction head. Training proceeds in two phases: (1) bidirectional masked infilling to learn rich representations, and (2) a causal variant for streams to close the train–test gap for online use.\n\nGraph adaptation: Represent each sample as a (possibly dynamic) attributed graph and apply structured masks over nodes, edges, attributes, and subgraphs. We preferentially sample masks as random-walk subgraphs and small edge cuts so the model must reason about topology, not just local attributes. The encoder is a message-passing or graph transformer that injects a learnable global token into per-node updates and the readout, so global context (e.g., session/user or scene/task state) is available during reconstruction. The decoder predicts masked node attributes (regression/classification), masked edge existence/types (link prediction), and the masked portion of any global attribute. High mask ratios (50–80%) are feasible with a light decoder, mirroring MAE-style efficiency while enforcing structural reasoning.\n\nTime series and sensor streams: Use a continuous-time encoder built on a Neural CDE front end to handle irregular sampling and multi-rate sensors. We train with discretely-online integration so the model remains causal at a target control/streaming frequency, but in phase 1 allow bidirectional context for representation learning. Masks combine (a) contiguous time spans at multiple scales, (b) channel-group drops to force cross-sensor reasoning, and (c) naturally missing segments treated as masks. To disambiguate concurrent sources (e.g., overlapping events in audio or multi-sensor interference), we add a mix-and-separate auxiliary task: form synthetic mixtures of two streams and train a shared backbone with a separation head to recover each source, alongside masked infilling. In phase 2, we switch a subset of masks to causal blocks (predict spans using only past) and keep the discretely-online evolution so the pretrained model can be deployed without violating causality.\n\nObjective design: Reconstruction heads predict appropriate targets per variable: categorical attributes via cross-entropy; continuous signals via heteroskedastic regression (predict mean and variance with a NLL loss) or Huber/quantile losses to avoid blurring. For oscillatory data (e.g., audio, vibration), add a phase/spectral term computed on short windows so the model matches both amplitude and phase rather than only time-domain MSE. For graphs, include link-prediction and small-motif classification losses to bias toward topology compliance. We use uncertainty-aware weighting to focus learning where the model is least certain: estimate a per-mask confidence from a lightweight latent prototype module or from predicted observation noise, and upweight high-uncertainty regions. Mask placement follows a curriculum: start with pointwise and short blocks, then grow to long spans and larger subgraphs; a tiny selector network identifies change-points or “core” segments (e.g., event onsets) and we occasionally center masks on these to force event-level reasoning. The total loss is a weighted sum of masked reconstruction, structural/phase terms, and the separation auxiliary.\n\nTraining and transfer: Phase 1 pretrains with high mask ratios and bidirectional context for sample efficiency. Phase 2 introduces causal masks for streams while keeping bidirectional graph pretraining. For downstream use, freeze or lightly tune the encoder and attach task-specific heads: node/graph classification, anomaly detection, forecasting, policy conditioning, or cross-sensor fusion. The same pretrained backbone supports both offline analytics (full-context) and online control/monitoring (causal), thanks to the discretely-online CDE evolution and the global token that stabilizes long-horizon context on graphs.",
  "rationale": "Masked prediction works by forcing a model to use global and long-range context to reconstruct missing information. On graphs, masking nodes/edges/subgraphs compels the encoder to internalize topology and attribute dependencies; injecting a global token ensures that local message passing is conditioned on session- or scene-level state, improving sample efficiency and downstream performance. On streams, contiguous block masks teach temporal dynamics and cross-sensor relationships; a continuous-time encoder preserves invariances to sampling rate and irregularity, while a discretely-online evolution keeps the pretrained model deployable under causality constraints.\n\nTwo design choices are pivotal: what to predict and where to mask. Predicting distributional targets and adding phase/spectral terms yield objectives aligned with perception and control rather than plain MSE. Event-aware and uncertainty-aware masking avoid overfitting to easy regions, increasing the value of each masked token. Finally, a mix-and-separate auxiliary resolves multi-source ambiguity—common in real sensors—so the backbone learns disentangled, source-aware features that transfer robustly.",
